<subsection xml:id="subsec-congruence-tests-for-triangles">
    <title>Congruence tests for triangles</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      Congruence in triangles depends on the measurement of the sides and angles.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two triangles are said to be congruent if a pair of the corresponding sides and corresponding angles are equal.
    </p>
    </introduction>
    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-conditions-for-congruence-in-triangles">
      <title>Conditions for congruence in triangles</title>
    <p>
      <term>1. SSS Criterion</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>SSS</term> stands for <term>side-side-side.</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this criterion, the three sides of one triangle is equal to the three sides of the corresponding triangle.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the figure below: 
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>AB</m> is equal to side <m>PQ</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>BC</m> is equal to side <m>QR</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>AC</m> is equal to side <m>PR</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <image>
      <latex-image label="side_side_side">
        \begin{tikzpicture}

          % Draw the original triangle
          \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
          \draw[blue,thick] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
          \node[blue] at (-2,3.1) {A};
          \node[blue] at (-4.1,0) {B};
          \node[blue] at (-0.9,-2.1) {C};

          \draw[black] (-3.1,1.6)--(-2.9,1.4);
          \draw[black] (-2.2,-1.3)--(-2.2,-1);
          \draw[black] (-2.5,-.8)--(-2.5,-1.2);
          \draw[black] (-1.8,1)--(-1.4,1);
          \draw[black] (-1.8,0.8)--(-1.4,.8);
          \draw[black] (-1.8,0.6)--(-1.4,.6);

          % Draw the another triangle
          \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (2,3) -- (4,0) -- (1,-2) -- cycle;
          \draw[blue,thick] (2,3) -- (4,0) -- (1,-2) -- cycle;
          \node[blue] at (2,3.1) {P};
          \node[blue] at (4.1,0) {Q};
          \node[blue] at (0.9,-2.1) {R};

          \draw[black] (3.1,1.6)--(2.9,1.4);
          \draw[black] (2.2,-1.3)--(2.2,-1);
          \draw[black] (2.5,-.8)--(2.5,-1.2);
          \draw[black] (1.8,1)--(1.4,1);
          \draw[black] (1.8,0.8)--(1.4,.8);
          \draw[black] (1.8,0.6)--(1.4,.6);

        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>
      Since the two triangles meet the <term>SSS</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR.</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>2. SAS Criterion</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>SAS</term> stands for <term>side-angle-side.</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this criterion, two sides and an included angle of one triangle is equal to the two corresponding sides and the included angle of the other triangle.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the figure below: 
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>AB</m> is equal to side <m>PR</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>BC</m> is equal to side <m>PQ</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle B</m> is equal to <m>\angle P</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <image>
      <latex-image label="side_angle_side">
        \begin{tikzpicture}

        \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

        % Triangle ABC
        \coordinate (A) at (-6,4);
        \coordinate (B) at (-8,1);
        \coordinate (C) at (-2,1);

        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (A) {A};
        \node[left] at (B) {B};
        \node[below right] at (C) {C};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=C--B--A};; 

        % Triangle PQR
        \coordinate (P) at (-2,4);
        \coordinate (Q) at (4,4);
        \coordinate (R) at (0,1);

        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (P) {P};
        \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
        \node[below right] at (R) {R};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=R--P--Q};; 

        \draw[black] (-7,3)--(-6.5,2.6); 

        \draw[black] (-5.4,.7)--(-5.4,1.3); 
        \draw[black] (-5.2,.7)--(-5.2,1.3); 

        \draw[black] (0.5,3.8)--(0.5,4.2); 
        \draw[black] (0.6,3.8)--(0.6,4.2); 

         \draw[black] (-1.2,2.4)--(-0.8,2.6); 
                  
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      Therefore, by <term>SAS</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR.</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>3. ASA Criterion</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>ASA</term> stands for <term>angle-side-angle.</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this criterion, one side and two included angles of one triangle is equal to the corresponding side and the two included angles of the other triangle.
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>AB</m> is equal to side <m>PQ</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle B</m> is equal to <m>\angle P</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle A</m> is equal to <m>\angle Q</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <image>
      <latex-image label="angle_side_angle">
        \begin{tikzpicture}

        \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

        % Triangle ABC
        \coordinate (A) at (-4,4);
        \coordinate (B) at (-1,1);
        \coordinate (C) at (-8,1);

        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (A) {A};
        \node[right] at (B) {B};
        \node[below right] at (C) {C};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=C--A--B};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=A--B--C};; 

        % Triangle PQR
        \coordinate (P) at (0,1);
        \coordinate (Q) at (3,4);
        \coordinate (R) at (7,1);

        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (P) {P};
        \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
        \node[below right] at (R) {R};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=R--P--Q};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=P--Q--R};; 

        \draw[black] (-2.6,2.4)--(-2.4,2.6); 

        \draw[black] (1.8,2.6)--(1.6,2.8);  
                  
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>
      Therefore, by <term>ASA</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR.</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>4. RHS Criterion</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>RHS</term> stands for <term>right angle-hypotenuse-side.</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this criterion, one side and the hypotenuse of a right-angled triangle are equal to the hypotenuse and the corresponding side of another right-angled triangle.
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>AC</m> is equal to side <m>PR</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>BC</m> is equal to side <m>RQ</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle B</m> is equal to <m>\angle Q</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      By <term>RHS</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR</m> and sides <m>AB</m> is equal to side <m>PQ.</m> 
      <m>\angle A \text{ is equal to } \angle P.</m> Therefore, this means that <m>\angle C \text{ is equal to } \angle R.</m>
    </p>

    <image>
      <latex-image label="RHS">
        \begin{tikzpicture}

        \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

        % Triangle ABC
        \coordinate (A) at (-5,5);
        \coordinate (B) at (-5,0);
        \coordinate (C) at (-1,0);

        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (A) {A};
        \node[left] at (B) {B};
        \node[below right] at (C) {C};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=B--A--C};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] (-4.6,0) -- (-4.6,0.4) -- (-5,0.4); 

        % Triangle PQR
        \coordinate (P) at (4,5);
        \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
        \coordinate (R) at (0,0);

        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (P) {P};
        \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
        \node[below right] at (R) {R};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=R--P--Q};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] (3.6,0) -- (3.6,0.4) -- (4,0.4); 

        \draw[black] (-2.6,-.2)--(-2.6,.2); 
        \draw[black] (-2.4,-.2)--(-2.4,.2);

        \draw[black] (2.6,-.2)--(2.6,.2); 
        \draw[black] (2.4,-.2)--(2.4,.2);

        \draw[black] (-3,2.2)--(-2.8,2.4);  

        \draw[black] (2,2)--(1.6,2.4);  
                  
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>
      Therefore, by <term>RHS</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR.</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>5. AAS Criterion</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>AAS</term> stands for <term>angle-angle-side.</term>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this criterion, one side and two included angles of one triangle is equal to the corresponding side and the two included angles of the other triangle.
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Side <m>CB</m> is equal to side <m>PR</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle B</m> is equal to <m>\angle P</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\angle A</m> is equal to <m>\angle Q</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <image>
      <latex-image label="angle_angle_side">
        \begin{tikzpicture}

        \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

        % Triangle ABC
        \coordinate (A) at (-4,4);
        \coordinate (B) at (-1,1);
        \coordinate (C) at (-8,1);

        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (A) {A};
        \node[right] at (B) {B};
        \node[below right] at (C) {C};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=C--A--B};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=A--B--C};; 

        % Triangle PQR
        \coordinate (P) at (0,1);
        \coordinate (Q) at (3,4);
        \coordinate (R) at (7,1);

        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
        \node[above] at (P) {P};
        \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
        \node[below right] at (R) {R};

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=blue, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=R--P--Q};; 

        \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
         {angle=P--Q--R};; 

        \draw[black] (-4.5,.8)--(-4.5,1.2); 

        \draw[black] (3.5,0.8)--(3.5,1.2);  
                  
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>
      Therefore, by <term>AAS</term> criterion, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR.</m>
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check if the triangles below are congruent and state the test of congruence criterion.
        </p>

        <image>
        <latex-image label="side_angle_side_exercise1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}

          \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

          % Triangle ABC
          \coordinate (A) at (-6,4);
          \coordinate (B) at (-8,1);
          \coordinate (C) at (-2,1);

          \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
          \node[above] at (A) {A};
          \node[left] at (B) {B};
          \node[below right] at (C) {C};

          \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(A)(B)(C)} pic["$60^\circ$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
          {angle=C--B--A};; 

          % Triangle PQR
          \coordinate (P) at (-2,4);
          \coordinate (Q) at (4,4);
          \coordinate (R) at (0,1);

          \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;
          \node[above] at (P) {P};
          \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
          \node[below right] at (R) {R};

          \draw[draw=blue] plot coordinates{(P)(Q)(R)} pic["$60^\circ$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=1cm]
          {angle=R--P--Q};; 

          \draw node at(-7,3) {$3\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (-5.4,.7) {$8\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (0.5,4.2) {$8\, cm$}; 

          \draw node at (-1.2,2.4) {$3\, cm$}; 
                    
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
     </statement>
     <solution>
      <p>
          From the figure, identify corresponding sides and angles.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sides <m>AB = PR = 3\, cm \text{ and } BC = PQ = 8\,cm</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\angle B = \angle P = 60^\circ.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, <m>\Delta ABC \cong \Delta PQR</m> by <term>SAS</term> criterion
        </p>
     </solution>
    </example>
  
